00:17:39,240 --> 00:17:40,680
Well, the supermarket
security officer

264
00:17:40,760 --> 00:17:43,360
and one of the checkers remembers
these 3 characters leaving

265
00:17:43,440 --> 00:17:45,160
right after Mrs. Kersey
and your daughter.

266
00:17:45,240 --> 00:17:47,680
They think they could have gotten
the apartment number

267
00:17:47,760 --> 00:17:49,480
off the address
on the grocery bags,

268
00:17:49,560 --> 00:17:52,240
but they haven't been able to
pick the faces out of the mug book.

269
00:17:52,320 --> 00:17:54,280
How is your daughter,
Mr. Kersey?

270
00:17:54,360 --> 00:17:56,880
She's under
doctor's sedation right now.

271
00:17:57,920 --> 00:17:59,880
But today
I had the funeral

272
00:17:59,960 --> 00:18:01,720
for my wife
up in Connecticut,

273
00:18:01,800 --> 00:18:03,440
and she was able
to make that.

274
00:18:03,520 --> 00:18:06,760
Your daughter didn't give us
much information, Mr. Kersey.

275
00:18:06,840 --> 00:18:10,200
We wish we could persuade her
to take a look at the mug books.

276
00:18:10,280 --> 00:18:11,480
Did she refuse?

277
00:18:11,560 --> 00:18:14,120
Her husband asked us
to wait for a few days.

278
00:18:14,200 --> 00:18:16,760
In fact, the sooner she looks
at the mug books,

279
00:18:16,840 --> 00:18:19,840
the better chance she has
of recalling one or 2 of the faces.

280
00:18:20,960 --> 00:18:23,240
Well, I'll talk
to my son-in-law

281
00:18:23,320 --> 00:18:25,480
and see what
can be done.

282
00:18:25,560 --> 00:18:27,320
I'd appreciate that,
Mr. Kersey.

283
00:18:27,400 --> 00:18:30,880
Is there any chance
of catching these men?

284
00:18:32,040 --> 00:18:33,600
There's a chance.
Sure.

285
00:18:33,680 --> 00:18:35,960
Just a chance?

286
00:18:36,040 --> 00:18:38,680
I'd be less than honest if I gave you
more hope, Mr. Kersey.

287
00:18:38,760 --> 00:18:42,320
In the city,
that's the way it is.

288
00:18:53,480 --> 00:18:55,240
I thought
you were asleep.

289
00:18:56,720 --> 00:18:59,000
Aahhh!

290
00:18:59,080 --> 00:19:01,800
TV: Are you getting
the most out of life?

291
00:19:01,880 --> 00:19:04,880
Are you satisfied,
fulfilled, happy?

292
00:19:04,960 --> 00:19:07,720
Our bank has helped many
to a better future.

293
00:19:33,160 --> 00:19:35,840
[Object Falls On Pavement]

294
00:19:59,760 --> 00:20:01,280
Good morning,
Mr. Kersey.

295
00:20:01,360 --> 00:20:02,480
Good morning.

296
00:20:02,560 --> 00:20:06,240
Would you give me
$20 in quarters, please?

297
00:20:17,960 --> 00:20:19,200
[Door Opens]

298
00:20:20,360 --> 00:20:21,840
Good morning,
Paul.

299
00:20:21,920 --> 00:20:22,920
Morning.

300
00:20:23,960 --> 00:20:24,880
Paul, you're tough.

301
00:20:24,960 --> 00:20:26,520
You know,
you really are.

302
00:20:26,600 --> 00:20:28,760
I told Ives
you'd come in this morning.

303
00:20:28,840 --> 00:20:30,760
I said Paul is not
the kind of man

304
00:20:30,840 --> 00:20:32,840
to leave the pieces of his
life lying around.

305
00:20:32,920 --> 00:20:34,480
He'll just start
picking them up.

306
00:20:34,560 --> 00:20:36,800
Just a matter
of keeping busy, Sam.

307
00:20:38,240 --> 00:20:39,600
Paul,
welcome back.

308
00:20:39,680 --> 00:20:41,040
Good morning,
Henry.

309
00:20:41,120 --> 00:20:42,800
See you
for lunch, Paul?

310
00:20:42,880 --> 00:20:43,800
Yeah. Sure.

311
00:20:43,880 --> 00:20:46,080
Paul, I'm going to
give you a vacation.

312
00:20:46,160 --> 00:20:47,760
From New York,
that is.

313
00:20:47,840 --> 00:20:51,320
The Jainchill development
of Tucson, Arizona:

314
00:20:51,400 --> 00:20:53,360
I want you
to take it over...

315
00:20:53,440 --> 00:20:54,960
redesign it,
if necessary.

316
00:20:55,040 --> 00:20:56,440
Whatever
you have to do.

317
00:20:56,520 --> 00:20:57,840
All right?

318
00:20:57,920 --> 00:20:59,000
That's all right,

319
00:20:59,080 --> 00:21:01,680
but can I give you
an answer in about a week?

320
00:21:01,760 --> 00:21:03,920
I don't want to leave New York
just now because of Carol.

321
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:05,120
Fine.

322
00:21:05,200 --> 00:21:07,360
When you're ready,
let me know.

323
00:21:07,440 --> 00:21:09,080
Beautiful place,
Tucson.

324
00:21:09,160 --> 00:21:10,800
They can breathe
out there.

325
00:21:19,880 --> 00:21:22,240
She's sleeping
too much.

326
00:21:22,320 --> 00:21:23,680
It's not normal.

327
00:21:23,760 --> 00:21:26,080
I've got a couple
of TV dinners in the oven.

328
00:21:26,160 --> 00:21:27,040
Come on.

329
00:21:27,120 --> 00:21:29,280
It will just be
a couple of minutes.

330
00:21:30,960 --> 00:21:33,280
Jack, this drink's
enough for me.

331
00:21:33,360 --> 00:21:35,680
I've never seen you drink
without eating.

332
00:21:35,760 --> 00:21:37,600
I'm not hungry.

333
00:21:37,680 --> 00:21:41,920
I think maybe you ought to take
Carol to see another doctor.

334
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:44,800
I did. Today.

335
00:21:44,880 --> 00:21:46,720
A psychiatrist.

336
00:21:46,800 --> 00:21:49,120
He seems to feel
it might help her

337
00:21:49,200 --> 00:21:51,520
if I took her away
to another environment...

338
00:21:51,600 --> 00:21:55,360
out of New York,
on the shore someplace.

339
00:21:55,440 --> 00:21:56,800
Sounds like
a good idea.

340
00:21:56,880 --> 00:21:58,280
I'll go along
with you.

341
00:21:58,360 --> 00:22:00,160
Uh, no, Dad.

342
00:22:00,240 --> 00:22:02,520
He seemed to feel
that it might be better

343
00:22:02,600 --> 00:22:04,680
if she didn't have
any association with anyone

344
00:22:04,760 --> 00:22:06,680
that might remind
her of that day.

345
00:22:06,760 --> 00:22:09,400
How the hell do I
remind her of that day?

346
00:22:09,480 --> 00:22:11,640
Well, you know
how it is, Dad.

347
00:22:11,720 --> 00:22:13,760
It happened
in your apartment.

348
00:22:13,840 --> 00:22:15,920
And you're
living there.

349
00:22:16,000 --> 00:22:17,920
You remind her
of Mom.

350
00:22:20,320 --> 00:22:22,560
Dad, don't make it
tough for me.

351
00:22:24,680 --> 00:22:27,080
OK, I'll make it
easy for you.

352
00:22:27,160 --> 00:22:31,000
Ives asked me to go
to Tucson, Arizona, on a job.

353
00:22:31,080 --> 00:22:32,800
How long
will you be gone?

354
00:22:32,880 --> 00:22:35,160
I don't know...
until I look the job over.

355
00:22:35,240 --> 00:22:36,600
But you call me
every other day.

356
00:22:36,680 --> 00:22:38,040
Let me know
how Carol is.

357
00:22:38,120 --> 00:22:40,920
Sure I will, Dad.

358
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:43,320
You know, that will
be good for you.

359
00:22:43,400 --> 00:22:45,320
I hear Tucson's
a really beautiful place.

360
00:22:45,400 --> 00:22:47,120
Yeah, yeah.
That's what everybody says.

361
00:22:54,920 --> 00:22:56,840
How are you
today, sir?

362
00:23:39,800 --> 00:23:41,600
Son of a bitch.

363
00:23:41,680 --> 00:23:44,320
Turn around,
son of a bitch.

364
00:23:44,400 --> 00:23:45,320
Motherfucker!

365
00:23:45,400 --> 00:23:46,520
I said
turn around.

366
00:23:46,600 --> 00:23:48,360
Now hand me
the money.

367
00:23:52,920 --> 00:23:53,880
Aah!

368
00:25:11,400 --> 00:25:12,720
Paul Kersey.

369
00:25:12,800 --> 00:25:13,680
Yeah.

370
00:25:13,760 --> 00:25:14,640
Aimes Jainchill.

371
00:25:14,720 --> 00:25:16,240
How do you do,
Mr. Jainchill?

372
00:25:16,320 --> 00:25:17,680
Aimes.
I'll call you Paul.

373
00:25:17,760 --> 00:25:19,120
Come on.
Let's get your bags.

374
00:25:19,200 --> 00:25:20,920
How did you know
who I was?

375
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:22,360
Well, you look like
a New Yorker.

376
00:25:22,440 --> 00:25:24,400
[Cattle Mooing]

377
00:25:30,680 --> 00:25:31,760
Ho!

378
00:25:38,400 --> 00:25:39,680
Howdy, Jud.

379
00:25:47,080 --> 00:25:49,080
I wanted you
to see this country

380
00:25:49,160 --> 00:25:52,560
before you looked at the
drawings back at the office.

381
00:25:52,640 --> 00:25:54,280
Give you
a better idea.

382
00:25:54,360 --> 00:25:56,320
I don't want to
change these hills.

383
00:25:56,400 --> 00:25:58,400
Don't want to
bulldoze them flat.

384
00:26:01,400 --> 00:26:03,680
You'll waste a lot
of building space.

385
00:26:03,760 --> 00:26:05,600
Ha ha!

386
00:26:05,680 --> 00:26:07,040
Wasting space.

387
00:26:07,120 --> 00:26:09,640
Now, those are some words
that you big developers

388
00:26:09,720 --> 00:26:11,960
have got to change
for something else.

389
00:26:12,040 --> 00:26:13,720
Such as?

390
00:26:13,800 --> 00:26:15,200
Well,
space for life.

391
00:26:15,280 --> 00:26:17,080
Like old Jud
up there.

392
00:26:17,160 --> 00:26:20,200
Space for people,
horses, cows.

393
00:26:20,280 --> 00:26:23,520
I got funny ideas
about building things.

394
00:26:29,680 --> 00:26:30,880
Man: Howdy, folks.

395
00:26:30,960 --> 00:26:32,480
Welcome to Old Tucson,

396
00:26:32,560 --> 00:26:34,040
the famous movie location
and studio.

397
00:26:34,120 --> 00:26:35,640
In just a few moments...

398
00:26:35,720 --> 00:26:37,160
Come on.
Let's wet our whistle

399
00:26:37,240 --> 00:26:38,640
before I trot you
back to the motel.

400
00:26:38,720 --> 00:26:40,080
Glass of beer,
maybe.

401
00:26:40,160 --> 00:26:41,880
Announcer: ...take their positions
on the porches and boardwalks

402
00:26:41,960 --> 00:26:44,680
of the Red Dog Cafe,
the territorial gunsmith shop...

403
00:26:44,760 --> 00:26:46,520
What's happening here?

404
00:26:46,600 --> 00:26:48,240
Oh, it's a phony
western town.

405
00:26:48,320 --> 00:26:49,600
They shoot movies
here sometimes,

406
00:26:49,680 --> 00:26:52,360
but the rest of the time
it's for the tourists.

407
00:26:52,440 --> 00:26:55,520
Announcer: this is where the
actual performance will take place.

408
00:26:55,600 --> 00:26:56,920
These fellas
are pretty good.

409
00:26:57,000 --> 00:26:58,440
You want
to watch this?

410
00:26:58,520 --> 00:27:00,400
Announcer:
the Wild West lives again.

411
00:27:00,480 --> 00:27:02,040
Man: Where's the Marshal?

412
00:27:02,120 --> 00:27:03,760
Second Man:
He's in the bank.

413
00:27:03,840 --> 00:27:05,760
I spotted him through
the window as I came by.

414
00:27:05,840 --> 00:27:07,880
What have you
got in mind to do, then?

415
00:27:07,960 --> 00:27:09,800
Well, why don't you
steal my horse?

416
00:27:09,880 --> 00:27:11,800
All right.
That's a good trick. We'll use it.

417
00:27:11,880 --> 00:27:13,320
You spot yourself
on the porch

418
00:27:13,400 --> 00:27:15,320
while I draw the marshal
out into the open.

419
00:27:15,400 --> 00:27:17,040
Marshal!
Hey, Marshal!

420
00:27:17,120 --> 00:27:18,800
Marshal:
What's the matter, fella?

421
00:27:18,880 --> 00:27:20,600
Somebody
stole my horse.

422
00:27:20,680 --> 00:27:23,600
Marshal: I told you
to get out of town by sunset.

423
00:27:23,680 --> 00:27:26,360
Man: You missing a bay mare
that was tied to the hitching rail?

424
00:27:26,440 --> 00:27:29,160
Saw a feller come and
take her just a spell ago.

425
00:27:29,240 --> 00:27:31,160
Marshal: well,
what did he look like?

426
00:27:31,240 --> 00:27:33,120
Well, he was
about this tall, and he had this...

427
00:27:33,200 --> 00:27:34,720
Get him, Frank!

428
00:27:56,640 --> 00:27:58,600
Let's put him
inside here

429
00:27:58,680 --> 00:28:01,320
and get to the bank
and make that withdrawal.

430
00:28:06,360 --> 00:28:08,800
Marshal: All right,
boys. The fun's over.

431
00:28:08,880 --> 00:28:12,120
Throw out your guns,
and step out with your hands up.

432
00:28:12,200 --> 00:28:13,400
You'd better listen,
Marshal.

433
00:28:13,480 --> 00:28:14,920
I've got 3 sticks
of dynamite here.

434
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:16,480
Don't be a fool.

435
00:28:32,960 --> 00:28:35,480
Announcer: The outlaw life
seemed a shortcut to easy money,

436
00:28:35,560 --> 00:28:37,440
which could buy
liquor, women,

437
00:28:37,520 --> 00:28:39,440
and a turn
at the gambling table,

438
00:28:39,520 --> 00:28:41,240
but there were
honest men with dreams

439
00:28:41,320 --> 00:28:43,280
who would fight
to protect their...

440
00:28:43,360 --> 00:28:44,920
Let's get that beer.

441
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:48,120
Announcer: ...and who were to plant
the roots that would grow into a nation.

442
00:28:54,280 --> 00:28:56,560
Blue Ridge won't buy it.

443
00:28:58,040 --> 00:29:02,040
I don't build a thing that's going
to be a slum in 20 years,

444
00:29:02,120 --> 00:29:04,200
and I won't
doze those hills.

445
00:29:04,280 --> 00:29:06,520
What I build
conforms to the land.

446
00:29:06,600 --> 00:29:09,440
And you can't hear
the toilets flush next door.

447
00:29:10,840 --> 00:29:12,200
You want our help,

448
00:29:12,280 --> 00:29:15,080
you'll have to
let me work with it.

449
00:29:15,160 --> 00:29:17,560
Well, up to a point,
I want your help.

450
00:29:17,640 --> 00:29:20,040
Up to a point,
I'll give it to you.

451
00:30:09,480 --> 00:30:11,320
When do I get
a look-see?

452
00:30:12,840 --> 00:30:14,840
In a couple days.

453
00:30:14,920 --> 00:30:17,880
Guard says you were here
till after midnight last night.

454
00:30:17,960 --> 00:30:19,640
Yeah. That's
the way I work.

455
00:30:19,720 --> 00:30:23,160
Somebody once said... I forget who...
that he never looked back

456
00:30:23,240 --> 00:30:26,320
because something might
be gaining on him.

457
00:30:26,400 --> 00:30:28,800
What's gaining
on you, Paul?

458
00:30:30,720 --> 00:30:33,240
$20 million investment.
What else?

459
00:30:33,320 --> 00:30:35,240
Well, I was
going to ask you

460
00:30:35,320 --> 00:30:37,400
to have dinner
with me at the club,

461
00:30:37,480 --> 00:30:39,720
but I don't think
you'd be very good company.

462
00:30:39,800 --> 00:30:41,160
No, I don't think
I would.

463
00:30:41,240 --> 00:30:42,520
It might amuse you,
though.

464
00:30:42,600 --> 00:30:45,840
Being from New York,
maybe you never seen a club like this.

465
00:30:45,920 --> 00:30:48,560
It's a gun club.
We shoot guns.

466
00:30:52,000 --> 00:30:54,960
So goddamn much hoopla
from the gun control people.

467
00:30:55,040 --> 00:30:57,680
Half the nation's scared
to even <i>hold</i> a gun!

468
00:30:57,760 --> 00:30:59,600
You know,
like it was a snake,

469
00:30:59,680 --> 00:31:02,000
it was going to bite
you or something.

470
00:31:02,080 --> 00:31:04,400
Hell, a gun
is just a tool...

471
00:31:04,480 --> 00:31:06,320
Like a hammer
or an ax.

472
00:31:06,400 --> 00:31:09,440
Wasn't long ago,
used to put food on the table,

473
00:31:09,520 --> 00:31:11,440
keep foxes out
of the chicken coop,

474
00:31:11,520 --> 00:31:12,720
rustlers off the range,

475
00:31:12,800 --> 00:31:14,320
bandits out of the bank.

476
00:31:14,400 --> 00:31:17,400
Paul, how long since you held
a pistol in your hand?

477
00:31:17,480 --> 00:31:19,760
A long time.

478
00:31:21,760 --> 00:31:23,600
Which war was yours...
Korea?

479
00:31:23,680 --> 00:31:24,720
Yeah.

480
00:31:24,800 --> 00:31:26,160
See much action?

481
00:31:26,240 --> 00:31:27,440
A little.

482
00:31:27,520 --> 00:31:28,880
In the infantry?

483
00:31:30,400 --> 00:31:33,200
I was a C.O.
in a medical unit.

484
00:31:33,280 --> 00:31:36,000
Oh, commanding
officer, huh?

485
00:31:36,080 --> 00:31:38,880
Conscientious objector.

486
00:31:38,960 --> 00:31:40,720
Oh, Christ.

487
00:31:40,800 --> 00:31:44,160
What a guest to bring
to a gun club!

488
00:31:44,240 --> 00:31:46,720
You're probably one
of them knee-jerk liberals

489
00:31:46,800 --> 00:31:48,920
thinks us gun boys
shoot our guns

490
00:31:49,000 --> 00:31:51,200
because it's an extension
of our penises.

491
00:31:51,280 --> 00:31:53,280
I never thought
about it that way,

492
00:31:53,360 --> 00:31:54,840
but it could be true.

493
00:31:54,920 --> 00:31:57,120
Well, maybe it is,

494
00:31:57,200 --> 00:31:59,360
but this is gun country.

495
00:31:59,440 --> 00:32:01,760
Can't even own a handgun
in New York City.

496
00:32:01,840 --> 00:32:04,320
Out here, I hardly know a man
that <i>doesn't</i> own one,

497
00:32:04,400 --> 00:32:05,760
and I'll tell you
something...

498
00:32:05,840 --> 00:32:08,160
Unlike your city,
we can walk our streets

499
00:32:08,240 --> 00:32:10,560
and through our parks at night
and feel safe.

500
00:32:10,640 --> 00:32:12,480
Muggers operating
out here,

501
00:32:12,560 --> 00:32:15,840
they just plain get
their asses blown off.

502
00:32:15,920 --> 00:32:17,760
Here. Slip these on.

503
00:32:17,840 --> 00:32:21,120
All righty. This is
a percussion pistol.

504
00:32:21,200 --> 00:32:22,680
1842.

505
00:32:25,680 --> 00:32:29,280
You ever handled
one of those before?

506
00:32:29,360 --> 00:32:31,840
You know
how to fire it?

507
00:32:31,920 --> 00:32:33,440
Watch the kick.

508
00:32:33,520 --> 00:32:35,000
Boy, you're
going to think

509
00:32:35,080 --> 00:32:37,880
that your arm's
going to hit the ceiling.

510
00:32:46,080 --> 00:32:47,960
Goddamn!

511
00:32:48,040 --> 00:32:49,560
Paul, you hit
dead center!

512
00:32:49,640 --> 00:32:51,800
Mind if I try
this hogleg Colt?

513
00:32:51,880 --> 00:32:53,240
No.

514
00:32:53,320 --> 00:32:56,600
Well, you a peculiar
conscientious objector.

515
00:32:56,680 --> 00:32:58,520
These notches
for real?

516
00:32:58,600 --> 00:33:02,360
Yeah. Belonged to a gunfighter
named Candy Dan, 1890.

517
00:33:02,440 --> 00:33:03,320
Hmm.

518
00:33:03,400 --> 00:33:05,720
I do know something
about guns, Aimes.

519
00:33:05,800 --> 00:33:09,080
I grew up with them...
all kinds of guns.

520
00:33:09,160 --> 00:33:11,480
You see, my father
was a hunter.

521
00:33:11,560 --> 00:33:14,360
I guess out here
you'd call him a gunman.

522
00:33:14,440 --> 00:33:17,320
My mother was
the other side of the coin.

523
00:33:17,400 --> 00:33:21,080
When my father was killed
in a hunting accident...

524
00:33:21,160 --> 00:33:23,960
some fool mistook him
for a deer, you see...

525
00:33:24,040 --> 00:33:26,840
my mother
won the toss.

526
00:33:26,920 --> 00:33:29,600
I never touched
a gun since.

527
00:33:29,680 --> 00:33:32,040
I loved my father.

528
00:33:41,280 --> 00:33:43,560
[Telephone Rings]

529
00:33:43,640 --> 00:33:45,480
There are your hills.

530
00:33:45,560 --> 00:33:48,680
Every house has a part
of one for a backyard,

531
00:33:48,760 --> 00:33:50,520
for kids, dogs, horses.

532
00:33:50,600 --> 00:33:54,120
400 houses, 100 more
than you allowed for,

533
00:33:54,200 --> 00:33:56,040
and you still have 12 hills.

534
00:33:57,880 --> 00:34:00,600
I'm catching the 10:40
back to New York.

535
00:34:00,680 --> 00:34:03,120
What do I tell them?

536
00:34:03,200 --> 00:34:06,600
You tell them
I'll buy it if they will.

537
00:34:24,440 --> 00:34:26,840
You're checking this bag
through, aren't you?

538
00:34:26,920 --> 00:34:27,800
Yeah.

539
00:34:27,880 --> 00:34:29,120
Good.

540
00:34:29,200 --> 00:34:32,600
Let me slip a little going-away
present in there for you.

541
00:34:32,680 --> 00:34:34,720
Thank you.

542
00:34:39,400 --> 00:34:41,560
P.A.: Trans World Airlines
flight 63

543
00:34:41,640 --> 00:34:43,480
from Tucson to New York
is now boarding...

544
00:34:43,560 --> 00:34:45,720
Good morning, sir.
How are you today?

545
00:34:45,800 --> 00:34:47,080
Checking one bag?

546
00:34:47,160 --> 00:34:48,920
Paul, I can't
thank you enough

547
00:34:49,000 --> 00:34:50,840
for what
you did for me.

548
00:34:50,920 --> 00:34:55,480
I want you to know if you ever
get tired of living in that toilet,

549
00:34:55,560 --> 00:34:58,080
you're welcome here.

550
00:34:59,880 --> 00:35:02,200
P.A.: Trans World Airlines
flight 7

551
00:35:02,280 --> 00:35:04,600
to London and Frankfurt
is now boarding.

552
00:35:04,680 --> 00:35:07,000
Passengers should proceed
to gate 11...

553
00:35:07,080 --> 00:35:08,440
Welcome home, Dad.

554
00:35:08,520 --> 00:35:11,320
Hi, Jack.
I halfway expected to see Carol.

555
00:35:11,400 --> 00:35:13,600
Come on.
Let's go get your bags.

556
00:35:15,080 --> 00:35:17,080
What is it?

557
00:35:17,160 --> 00:35:19,520
She's in the hospital.

558
00:35:21,000 --> 00:35:23,320
When I last spoke
to you on the phone,

559
00:35:23,400 --> 00:35:25,240
you said she
was feeling better

560
00:35:25,320 --> 00:35:27,120
after coming back
from the shore.

561
00:35:27,200 --> 00:35:30,480
Well, I didn't see any need
to get you all disturbed

562
00:35:30,560 --> 00:35:32,080
on a long-distance call.

563
00:35:32,160 --> 00:35:35,440
P.A.: Will Mr. Cory, a passenger
on Trans World Airlines flight 100

564
00:35:35,520 --> 00:35:37,200
from Vancouver,
please report to...

565
00:35:37,280 --> 00:35:39,960
Oh, come on, Dad,
don't do a number...

566
00:35:40,040 --> 00:35:42,000
Don't do
a number on me.

567
00:35:42,080 --> 00:35:44,560
Look, there was nothing
you could do.

568
00:35:44,640 --> 00:35:47,760
They haven't even
let <i>me</i> see her for 2 days.

569
00:35:50,240 --> 00:35:53,040
They tried insulin
shock yesterday.

570
00:35:53,120 --> 00:35:55,440
She's not
responding.

571
00:35:55,520 --> 00:35:57,360
You want the
technical jargon?

572
00:35:57,440 --> 00:35:59,760
I can reel off
yards of it:

573
00:35:59,840 --> 00:36:02,160
catatonia,
dementia praecox,

574
00:36:02,240 --> 00:36:05,040
passive
schizoid paranoia.

575
00:36:05,120 --> 00:36:07,280
It all boils down
to the fact

576
00:36:07,360 --> 00:36:10,160
that she's had an experience
that she can't face,

577
00:36:10,240 --> 00:36:13,040
and she's running away
from it inside herself.

578
00:36:13,120 --> 00:36:17,200
P.A.: Will Mrs. Lager, a passenger on
Trans World Airlines flight 45 to Paris,

579
00:36:17,280 --> 00:36:19,600
please contact
the information desk...

580
00:36:19,680 --> 00:36:21,840
You didn't handle her
right, Jack.

581
00:36:21,920 --> 00:36:24,960
Aw, Christ, Dad!

582
00:36:25,040 --> 00:36:27,520
I'll get other doctors.

583
00:36:27,600 --> 00:36:30,400
Who are these goddamn
doctors you have?

584
00:36:30,480 --> 00:36:32,240
They're good doctors!

585
00:36:34,960 --> 00:36:37,800
Dad, she's almost
a goddamn vegetable!

586
00:37:08,240 --> 00:37:11,680
If you don't sign
the papers, what happens?

587
00:37:13,360 --> 00:37:16,960
I guess they keep her in the hospital
until the insurance runs out.

588
00:37:17,040 --> 00:37:18,880
That won't be too long.

589
00:37:18,960 --> 00:37:22,680
If you sign the papers
and she's committed, what then?

590
00:37:22,760 --> 00:37:24,600
Well, I've got
an insurance policy

591
00:37:24,680 --> 00:37:27,480
that covers it up to
about 600 a month.

592
00:37:27,560 --> 00:37:30,840
They've recommended
a sanatorium out in Long Island.

593
00:37:30,920 --> 00:37:32,440
Jack...

594
00:37:34,120 --> 00:37:36,920
this commitment...
is it a one-way thing?

595
00:37:38,440 --> 00:37:40,440
Nobody can
answer that, Dad.

596
00:37:41,960 --> 00:37:44,280
You want to know
what they are?

597
00:37:44,360 --> 00:37:46,680
They're statistics
on a police blotter...

598
00:37:46,760 --> 00:37:50,520
Mom and Carol along with
thousands of other people.

599
00:37:50,600 --> 00:37:54,040
And there is nothing
that we can do to stop it.

600
00:37:54,120 --> 00:37:56,000
Nothing but cut and run.

601
00:40:14,200 --> 00:40:17,160
[Laughing]

602
00:40:18,280 --> 00:40:20,120
Boy: Oh,
what a bummer, man.

603
00:40:20,200 --> 00:40:23,040
That was the worst fucking movie
I've ever seen.

604
00:40:44,680 --> 00:40:47,520
[Faint Siren]

605
00:41:49,440 --> 00:41:51,280
You got money, man?

606
00:41:54,880 --> 00:41:56,760
Shit, I'll kill you!

607
00:41:56,840 --> 00:41:59,760
Give me your money,
or I'll bust you up!

608
00:42:12,240 --> 00:42:14,960
[Retching]

609
00:42:40,720 --> 00:42:42,560
Oh, Jesus.

610
00:42:42,640 --> 00:42:44,000
Oh, Jesus.

611
00:42:44,080 --> 00:42:45,920
Jesus Christ.

612
00:42:46,000 --> 00:42:47,360
Ohh...

613
00:42:47,440 --> 00:42:48,800
Oh, Jesus.

614
00:42:48,880 --> 00:42:50,720
Ahh...

615
00:42:50,800 --> 00:42:53,600
[Groaning]

616
00:43:05,200 --> 00:43:07,960
[Vomiting]

617
00:43:09,880 --> 00:43:12,760
[Indistinct Police Radio]

618
00:43:12,840 --> 00:43:16,480
[No Audible Dialogue]

619
00:43:21,960 --> 00:43:23,800
[Sneezes]

620
00:43:23,880 --> 00:43:25,720
Good morning, Inspector.

621
00:43:25,800 --> 00:43:27,640
Good morning.
What have we got?

622
00:43:27,720 --> 00:43:29,240
We got a corpse
down here,

623
00:43:29,320 --> 00:43:31,000
one bullet hole
in his chest.

624
00:43:31,080 --> 00:43:32,440
Fellow over there
was jogging

625
00:43:32,520 --> 00:43:33,880
through the park
at daybreak,

626
00:43:33,960 --> 00:43:35,320
found him
on the path here.

627
00:43:35,400 --> 00:43:37,240
You got a make
on the dead man?

628
00:43:37,320 --> 00:43:39,160
Yeah. His name is
Thomas Leroy Marston.

629
00:43:39,240 --> 00:43:40,600
He had a parole card.

630
00:43:40,680 --> 00:43:42,040
We got a radio check
on that.

631
00:43:42,120 --> 00:43:44,920
He served 42 months of a
5-year hitch for grand larceny.

632
00:43:45,000 --> 00:43:47,800
He's a drug addict.
He's probably popping smack again.

633
00:43:47,880 --> 00:43:49,240
There's punctures,
both arms.

634
00:43:49,320 --> 00:43:51,640
We found this
on the grass next to him.

635
00:43:51,720 --> 00:43:53,560
Thing hasn't been fired.

636
00:43:53,640 --> 00:43:56,280
Deceased had a gun
clip on his belt.

637
00:43:56,360 --> 00:43:57,880
Think it must be his.

638
00:43:57,960 --> 00:44:01,720
What would you say if I
suggested that he tried a heist,

639
00:44:01,800 --> 00:44:03,640
he got shot
for his trouble?

640
00:44:03,720 --> 00:44:06,440
Man: Maybe 2 guys trying
to heist each other.

641
00:44:06,520 --> 00:44:08,840
Inspector: No, no.
This man wasn't robbed.

642
00:44:08,920 --> 00:44:11,640
Still has money in his wallet.

643
00:44:33,280 --> 00:44:35,080
[Knock On Door]

644
00:44:35,160 --> 00:44:36,560
Good morning, Paul.

645
00:44:36,640 --> 00:44:37,680
Good morning.

646
00:44:37,760 --> 00:44:39,600
- Sam: Hi, Paul.
- Morning.

647
00:44:39,680 --> 00:44:40,720
Morning, Sam.

648
00:44:40,800 --> 00:44:44,400
Well, we've marked it out
as you've indicated.

649
00:44:44,480 --> 00:44:46,800
It's beautiful.

650
00:44:46,880 --> 00:44:48,720
What's our profit?

651
00:44:48,800 --> 00:44:50,640
Uh... not quite 3 million,

652
00:44:50,720 --> 00:44:52,560
but I believe that
our investment

653
00:44:52,640 --> 00:44:54,480
can be amortized
in 2 years,

654
00:44:54,560 --> 00:44:56,880
and it is a showplace
operation.

655
00:44:56,960 --> 00:44:58,800
Look at all that
wasted space.

656
00:44:58,880 --> 00:45:00,720
Jainchill loves those hills.

657
00:45:00,800 --> 00:45:03,520
Besides, it's a take-it-or-leave-it
proposition.

658
00:45:03,600 --> 00:45:05,760
Well, it's too pretty
to leave.

659
00:45:05,840 --> 00:45:08,160
OK. I'll run it
for the board.

660
00:45:08,240 --> 00:45:09,920
May need
your help, Paul.

661
00:45:10,000 --> 00:45:11,040
OK.

662
00:45:12,720 --> 00:45:15,520
Oh, Tucson agreed with you.
You look well.

663
00:45:15,600 --> 00:45:17,400
Paul: I feel, uh...

664
00:45:17,480 --> 00:45:18,880
good.

665
00:45:29,320 --> 00:45:32,640
[Scuffling]

666
00:45:32,720 --> 00:45:34,120
[Muffled Shout]

667
00:46:30,440 --> 00:46:33,240
[Siren]

668
00:46:35,720 --> 00:46:38,520
[People Shouting Questions]

669
00:46:45,800 --> 00:46:48,920
Man: Was he a white man
or a black man?

670
00:46:49,000 --> 00:46:50,680
Second Man:
I just don't know!

671
00:46:50,760 --> 00:46:52,920
Come on. They were
under that streetlight.

672
00:46:53,000 --> 00:46:55,800
I wasn't seeing too good.
I had blood in my eyes.

673
00:46:55,880 --> 00:46:57,640
Was he tall? Short?

674
00:46:57,720 --> 00:46:59,560
Thin? Fat?

675
00:46:59,640 --> 00:47:02,440
Hank, forget it, huh?

676
00:47:02,520 --> 00:47:05,320
Ride the ambulance
to the morgue.

677
00:47:05,400 --> 00:47:08,200
When they get the slugs
out of those bodies,

678
00:47:08,280 --> 00:47:11,080
run them over
to the lab for ballistics.

679
00:47:14,320 --> 00:47:17,480
[Siren]

680
00:47:17,560 --> 00:47:19,800
You saw him pretty good,
didn't you?

681
00:47:22,520 --> 00:47:24,360
You're full of shit.

682
00:48:23,640 --> 00:48:24,520
Thank you.

683
00:48:24,600 --> 00:48:25,480
Thank you.

684
00:48:28,440 --> 00:48:29,800
Ahh...

685
00:48:29,880 --> 00:48:33,640
You know, if we had the brains
to live here in the country,

686
00:48:33,720 --> 00:48:36,840
we wouldn't be here
for the reason we are today.

687
00:48:36,920 --> 00:48:39,400
We'd be going into
the city to work.

688
00:48:39,480 --> 00:48:41,800
Mom and Carol would
be safe at home,

689
00:48:41,880 --> 00:48:43,720
waiting for us
to come back.

690
00:48:43,800 --> 00:48:46,600
Nothing to do
but cut and run, huh?

691
00:48:46,680 --> 00:48:48,520
What else?

692
00:48:48,600 --> 00:48:52,800
What about the old American
social custom of self-defense?

693
00:48:52,880 --> 00:48:54,720
If the police
don't defend us,

694
00:48:54,800 --> 00:48:57,600
maybe we ought to
do it ourselves.

695
00:48:57,680 --> 00:49:00,480
We're not pioneers
anymore, Dad.

696
00:49:00,560 --> 00:49:02,880
What are we, Jack?

697
00:49:02,960 --> 00:49:04,800
What do you mean?

698
00:49:04,880 --> 00:49:08,640
I mean, if we're not pioneers,
what have we become?

699
00:49:08,720 --> 00:49:11,520
What do you call people...

700
00:49:11,600 --> 00:49:14,880
who, when they're faced
with a condition of fear,

701
00:49:14,960 --> 00:49:18,400
do nothing about it,
they just run and hide?

702
00:49:20,080 --> 00:49:21,600
Civilized?

703
00:49:25,040 --> 00:49:26,400
No.

704
00:49:30,800 --> 00:49:32,640
Ladies and gentlemen,

705
00:49:32,720 --> 00:49:36,000
we have to start this
investigation somewhere,

706
00:49:36,080 --> 00:49:37,920
so let's start here.

707
00:49:38,000 --> 00:49:39,840
[Siren Outside]

708
00:49:39,920 --> 00:49:42,720
[Coughs]

709
00:49:42,800 --> 00:49:44,640
Motive...

710
00:49:44,720 --> 00:49:46,560
revenge.

711
00:49:46,640 --> 00:49:48,960
I want the records checked.

712
00:49:49,040 --> 00:49:51,280
Go back, say, uh...

713
00:49:51,360 --> 00:49:53,200
3 months.

714
00:49:53,280 --> 00:49:55,600
Limit it to homicide.

715
00:49:55,680 --> 00:49:58,000
We could be looking
for a man

716
00:49:58,080 --> 00:50:02,320
who's had a member or members
of his family killed by muggers.

717
00:50:02,400 --> 00:50:06,640
Now, he shoots
that pistol pretty good.

718
00:50:06,720 --> 00:50:08,560
Right?

719
00:50:08,640 --> 00:50:10,160
OK.

720
00:50:10,240 --> 00:50:12,080
Combat veteran.

721
00:50:12,160 --> 00:50:15,280
So put Vietnam vets
at the top of the list,

722
00:50:15,360 --> 00:50:17,200
because they're youngest
and toughest.

723
00:50:17,280 --> 00:50:19,120
Then you can
work your way

724
00:50:19,200 --> 00:50:21,040
through Korea
and World War II.

725
00:50:21,120 --> 00:50:22,800
Oh, my God!

726
00:50:24,320 --> 00:50:26,000
Who said that?

727
00:50:26,080 --> 00:50:27,760
Hmm?

728
00:50:27,840 --> 00:50:30,640
Well, whoever said it,
you're right on the button.

729
00:50:30,720 --> 00:50:35,920
By God and Jesus Christ,
it's impossible,

730
00:50:36,000 --> 00:50:38,800
but until we find
a shortcut,

731
00:50:38,880 --> 00:50:41,200
we'll at least keep busy.

732
00:50:41,280 --> 00:50:46,160
So when the media demands to know what
we are doing to apprehend the vigilante,

733
00:50:46,240 --> 00:50:49,440
we'll tell them
we have definite clues.

734
00:50:49,520 --> 00:50:51,080
OK?

735
00:50:52,560 --> 00:50:56,000
We won't tell them we have
about a thousand definite clues.

736
00:53:27,640 --> 00:53:29,960
[Woman Screams]

737
00:53:31,120 --> 00:53:34,120
Man: There's a body in there...
2 of them!

738
00:53:47,600 --> 00:53:48,800
Where'd he go?

739
00:53:48,880 --> 00:53:50,760
Did anybody see
what he looked like?

740
00:53:50,840 --> 00:53:52,960
We are here in Police
Commissioner Dryer's office,

741
00:53:53,040 --> 00:53:55,840
waiting for a press conference
scheduled by Commissioner Dryer.

742
00:53:55,920 --> 00:53:58,080
Last night, there was
another double killing

743
00:53:58,160 --> 00:54:00,000
which appears
to be the work

744
00:54:00,080 --> 00:54:03,520
of the person New York news media
have dubbed "the vigilante".

745
00:54:03,600 --> 00:54:06,400
[Speaking Italian]

746
00:54:08,840 --> 00:54:11,680
[Speaking German]

747
00:54:13,640 --> 00:54:16,000
[Speaking French]

748
00:54:16,080 --> 00:54:18,360
American Announcer: This will be
the first official statement

749
00:54:18,440 --> 00:54:20,640
from Commissioner Dryer
on the vigilante killings.

750
00:54:20,720 --> 00:54:23,520
I can see the commissioner now
as he walks past...

751
00:54:23,600 --> 00:54:25,920
Commissioner: Good morning,
ladies and gentlemen.

752
00:54:26,000 --> 00:54:27,840
With me
is inspector Frank Ochoa,

753
00:54:27,920 --> 00:54:31,360
who has been placed in command
of a police detail

754
00:54:31,440 --> 00:54:36,400
assigned to what we've all
been calling the vigilante murders.

755
00:54:36,480 --> 00:54:40,560
Now, it has been confirmed
by our ballistics laboratory

756
00:54:40,640 --> 00:54:42,320
that the same gun,

757
00:54:42,400 --> 00:54:47,240
a .32 pistol which was used
in the previous 3 homicides,

758
00:54:47,320 --> 00:54:50,680
was used last night
in a shooting aboard a subway train.

759
00:54:50,760 --> 00:54:53,360
Now, I know
that this person

760
00:54:53,440 --> 00:54:57,680
has captured the imagination
of many people in our city,

761
00:54:57,760 --> 00:55:00,320
and I want to say
to our citizens,

762
00:55:00,400 --> 00:55:04,680
murder is no answer
to crime in this city.

763
00:55:04,760 --> 00:55:08,720
Crime is a police responsibility,

764
00:55:08,800 --> 00:55:12,000
and if this person
is listening to my voice,

765
00:55:12,080 --> 00:55:15,800
I urge him
in the name of law and order

766
00:55:15,880 --> 00:55:19,280
to desist
from this one-man crusade

767
00:55:19,360 --> 00:55:21,880
and turn himself in
to the police.

768
00:55:21,960 --> 00:55:24,080
He'll be given fair treatment.

769
00:55:24,160 --> 00:55:25,520
How do you like it?

770
00:55:25,600 --> 00:55:27,520
That's our police
commissioner, you know,

771
00:55:27,600 --> 00:55:29,560
that's Dryer...
the king of cliches.

772
00:55:29,640 --> 00:55:31,440
Reporter: Vigilante's identification?

773
00:55:31,520 --> 00:55:32,280
No comment at this time.

774
00:55:32,360 --> 00:55:34,560
Second Reporter:
Do you think this man's crazy?

775
00:55:34,640 --> 00:55:36,800
Well, he's got
a wire down, all right,

776
00:55:36,880 --> 00:55:39,520
but I don't believe we're dealing
with a raving maniac.

